{Nowadays, Grunfeld defense is one of the main weapons against 1.d4.  The
dynamic character of the position gives Black a chance not to play for the
equality, but even to seize the initiative in the opening if White goes wrong.
There are more than 20 systems, from which White can choose. There are always
some fashionable lines, which are popular for a couple of years and then
almost disappear. When I make an opening repertoire, I am trying to find a
system, which is long-lived. I found Russian System against the Grunfeld in
this way.  Whiteâ []s play is very logical and step on a solid position
background.    This system was a choice of almost any top player of all the
time. I will tell you just a couple of names: G. Kasparov, M.Carlsen,V. Anand,
A.Karpov, M.Botvinik, V.Smyslov.  In the provided repertoire, I verbally
explain all the ideas for both sides and try to show the reasons behind the
moves. This way you should not check every day in the database for some
novelties, but rather you have to understand the arising positions deeply and
know how to play them.    My goal is to avoid main lines and forcing
variations. Of course, this is not possible all the time, but this will be
minimized in the database.   Almost against any Blackâ []s system, I will
provide you continuations that are new and not very exposed with many
novelties and fresh ideas.   I believe that this database can be very useful
to a club player, who can find a lifetime repertoire against the Grunfeld
defense, but also this can help to a strong player to refresh his repertoire. 
Enjoy reading and I hope that you will have many wins with the Russian system
against Grunfeld.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 {This is the
starting position of the Russian system against Grunfeld.} dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7.
e4 {Black has a several options in this position.} a6 {Games 1 and 2.  This is
the most popular response. Black's plan is first to win some space on a
queenside and then to play c5. White can answer this by simply continue the
development and then with active play to try to seize the initiative.} (7...
Nc6 8. Be3 Bg4 {Game:3  Old main line almost disappeared from a high level
games. After a precise play White keep an advantage here.} (8... e5 $5 {Game 4:
Modern gambit which pose a lot of problems for White.  I am analyze sharp
positions and also offering a new idea after which White has  good chances to
play for a win, without any risk.})) (7... Na6 {Game 5 and 6  Prins variation.
Favourite choice of G.Kasparov and recently used by Magnus Carlsen caused a
lot of problems for White during the years.   I found some fresh ideas which
avoid long lines and provide great chances for an advantage.}) (7... Be6 {Game:
7  Provocative new line. As most of the variations in the database here I
offered some rare idea which score very well in practice.}) (7... Bg4 {Game 8:
Smyslov variation.   Long time ago this was a main line, but now White found a
couple of ways to play for the advantage.  I like an idea which appears very
soon in a serious tournament practice.}) (7... Nfd7 {Game:9  The famous
Smyslov maneuvre: î ..fd7-b6. It is too early for this. Almost anytime when
this î .. leaves the king side we can start an immediate attack.}) (7... c6 {
Game 10:  This move is just too slow. Without much efforts White  achieve a
better game.}) *

