1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 a6 {The
most popular continuation. Black's idea is to use the position of the queen
and to win a tempo through b7-b5 and after that quickly to push c7-c5.} {White
is at the crossroad, he can simply continue the development through 8. Be2 or
start active actions by e4-e5 and later e6.} 8. Be2 {We will look at the move
8.î Pe2, other option is 8.e5, but as I say the long forced variations are not
my taste.} b5 9. Qb3 c5 10. dxc5 {White temporarily has a pawn up and plans to
mobilize the forces while Black is trying to win the pawn back.} Be6 {Nowadays,
this is the main line.  The move 10...î Pb7 is analyzed in the next game. 
Black wins one more tempo for development. His following moves are î ..bd7 and
î Rc8. If White does not cause any threats, then Black can win the pawn back
and fight for the advantage. This is the reason why White's play should be
energetic and specific. You should remember that you should try to protect the
pawn by î Pe3 and î Rd1  before castling.} 11. Qc2 Nbd7 (11... Nc6 {This move
didn't attack c5 pawn and White can simply continue the development and keep
his advantage.} 12. O-O Qc7 13. h3 {Useful move.} b4 14. Na4 b3 15. axb3 Nb4
16. Qd2 a5 17. Nd4 Rad8 18. Nxe6 Rxd2 19. Nxc7 {1-0 (40) Leitao,R (2618)-Cori
Tello,J (2546) Manaus 2013}) (11... Qc7 12. Nd4 {White wins an important tempo
by attacking the "e6" bishop} Bc4 13. Be3 Bxe2 14. Ndxe2 Ng4 15. Nd5 Nxe3 16.
fxe3 Qe5 17. c6 {And White soon wins in the game:  1-0 (27) Ham,S (2358)-Laird,
E (2355) USA 1994}) 12. Be3 {Protecting the pawn.} (12. c6 $5 {A logical move,
but unfortunately it leads just to an equal game if Black plays precisely.} Nb8
13. Ng5 Nxc6 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Nxb5 Rc8 {The activity of black pieces
compensates the lack of the pawn.} 16. Nc3 Nd4 17. Qd3 Nd7 $1 18. O-O Nc5 19.
Qh3 Nxe2+ 20. Nxe2 Qd3 {1/2 (61) Volkov,S (2623)-Areshchenko,A (2688) Plovdiv
2012}) 12... Rc8 (12... Ng4 {This move was tried once by the GM Sutovski} 13.
Bd4 Nde5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rd1 Qa5 16. O-O Rfd8 {Instead of} 17. b3 $4 (17. Nd5
$1 $146 Bxd5 18. exd5 Qxa2 19. Bc3 {And White has a winning position.}) 17...
Rxd4 18. Rxd4 Nc6 19. Rdd1 Bxc3 $19 {0-1 (31) Ezat,M (2471)-Sutovsky,E (2657)
Bursa 2010}) 13. Rd1 (13. b4 $4 {A very common mistake made by the beginners
or in blitz games.} Nxe4 $1) 13... b4 14. Nd5 {This is wise decision. White
obtains a pair of bishops instead of trying to protect c5-pawn anymore.} (14.
Na4 {This move does not lead to advantage, as was seen in Svidler's game:} Qa5
15. O-O Nxe4 {After this strike, White cannot hope for more than an equality.}
16. c6 (16. Qxe4 Qxa4 {With multiple threats.}) 16... Nd6 {With complicate
position with mutual chances.  0-1 (40) Onischuk,A (2664)-Svidler,P (2746)
Foros 2008}) 14... Bxd5 15. exd5 Nxc5 16. O-O {How can we evaluate the
position.   White has a pair of bishops and Black's pawns on a queenside are
target of attack. With sure the position is easier to play with White pieces.}
Nce4 (16... a5 {Another possibility here is} 17. Bb5 $1 {The bishop is
directed to the "c6" square.} Nce4 18. Bc6 Nd6 19. Qe2 Qc7 {1-0 (35) Swapnil,S
(2438)-Gupta,A (2662) Kolkata 2012} (19... Nf5 20. Ne5 Qc7 21. f4 Nxe3 22. Qxe3
{White has a slight advantage.}) 20. Nd4 $146 {With the idea Bf4 and White has
clear advantage.}) 17. Qd3 (17. Qb3 {Interesting idea tested soon by L.
Aronian.} Qd6 (17... a5 {is followed by} 18. Ne5 Nc5 19. Bxc5 Rxc5 20. Bf3 Qd6
21. Rfe1 $14 {Followed by Nc4 and Nc6 and White has the initiative.}) 18. g3
Nc5 19. Qxb4 Nxd5 20. Qa3 Qc6 21. Bd4 Bxd4 22. Rxd4 {White is better, the pawn
on"a6" is weak and the black knights do not have reference squares.  1/2 (40)
Aronian,L (2765)-Areshchenko,A (2661) Baku 2015}) 17... Qd6 18. g3 {A modern
variation, the threat is obvious Bf4 on the next move.} (18. Qxa6 $1 {A very
interesting move that give White a slight advantage.} Rc2 (18... Ra8 19. Qc4
Rfc8 20. Qb3 {And Black does not have enough compensation for the sacrificed
pawn.}) 19. Bd4 Nc5 20. Qxd6 exd6 21. Bb5 Nfe4 {This is the critical position
of this line. Black is trying to compensate the lack of the pawn with the
activity of his pieces. If Black manages to equalize the material, the game
will end with a draw.} 22. Rc1 $1 {A very interesting idea of Indian
grandmaster.} ({This move was played many times.} 22. Ne1 Rd2 23. Bxg7 Rxd1 24.
Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Nf3 {White still has a slight initiative, however Black's
position is objectively defensible.} Rxd5 26. Bc4 Rf5 27. Nd4 Rf4 28. Ne2 Rf5
29. Ng3 Rf4 30. Ne2 Rf5 31. Ng3 Rf4 32. Ne2 {1/2 (32) Moiseenko,A (2701)
-Areshchenko,A (2655) Lvov 2014}) 22... Rxc1 23. Rxc1 {White exchanges Black's
active rook.} Bxd4 {This logical move turns to be a decisive mistake. White
remains with a healthy pawn up.} (23... Ra8 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. Ra1 Na4 {With
compensation for the pawn. White can safely enter in this position, because he
does not risk anything. The position is easy to play for us and Black should
be extremely careful of every move.}) 24. Nxd4 Ra8 25. f3 Nf6 26. Bc4 Na4 27.
Rc2 Nb6 28. Bb3 $16 {1-0 (46) Swapnil,S (2483)-Rajesh,V (2331) Bhubaneswar 2015
}) 18... Rfd8 19. Bf4 Qxd5 20. Qxa6 Qa8 21. Qxa8 Rxa8 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Rd1 $1
{An important improvement in the variation.} (23. Ne5 {This move does not
cause any serious troubles and Grischuk easily neutralized White's initiative
and ended the game with a draw:} Nd5 24. Rd1 Rd6 25. Nxg6 Nxf4 26. Nxf4 Rxd1+
27. Bxd1 Bxb2 28. Nd3 Bc3 29. Kg2 Kg7 30. f4 h6 31. g4 f5 32. gxf5 Nd6 33. Kf3
Kf6 34. Nf2 Kxf5 35. Ng4 Kg6 36. Bc2+ Kg7 37. Ne3 e6 38. Bb3 Nf5 39. Ke4 {1/2 
(39) Giri,A (2797)-Grischuk,A (2810) Tbilisi 2015}) 23... Nd5 (23... Rxd1+ 24.
Bxd1 Nd5 25. Bc1 e6 26. Kf1 {The engine assesses the position as a equal one,
but for a person is very unpleasant to play with black pieces. White has the
pair of bishops and a potential outside passed pawn.}) 24. Be5 (24. Bc4 e6 25.
Ne5 {With the idea Nc6, the position also looks unpleasant.}) 24... e6 25. Bxg7
Kxg7 26. Bc4 Rc8 27. Bb3 Nef6 28. Ne5 {White maintained a slight advantage,
which he converted not without the help of the opponent. Now, we will provide
you the full game without any further comments and you can enjoy the technical
playing of the Russian grandmaster.} g5 29. Rd4 Rc7 30. Kf1 Kf8 31. h4 h6 32.
Ke2 Kg7 33. Nd3 Rb7 34. Kd2 Kf8 35. Kc2 Rc7+ 36. Kd2 Rb7 37. hxg5 hxg5 38. Kc2
Rc7+ 39. Kd2 Rb7 40. Kc2 Rc7+ 41. Rc4 Rb7 42. Rc5 Ne7 43. Rc4 Ned5 44. Rc8+ Ke7
45. Bxd5 exd5 46. Kb3 Ne4 47. Rc2 f5 48. Nxb4 d4 49. Ka4 Rd7 50. Nd3 Ra7+ 51.
Kb5 Rxa2 52. Kc4 Ra6 53. Kxd4 Rd6+ 54. Ke3 Re6 55. Kd4 Rd6+ 56. Kc4 Rc6+ 57.
Kb3 Rd6 58. Nc5 Nxc5+ 59. Rxc5 Ke6 60. Kc2 Rd4 61. Rc3 f4 62. b3 Re4 63. Rd3 g4
64. Kc3 f3 65. b4 Re1 66. Rd2 Rb1 67. Rb2 Re1 68. b5 Kd7 69. Kd3 Kc7 70. Rb4
Re2 71. Rxg4 Rxf2 72. Ke3 Rb2 73. Kxf3 Rb3+ 74. Kg2 Rxb5 75. Rd4 Rb8 76. Kf3
Rf8+ 77. Ke4 Rg8 78. Kf4 Kc6 79. g4 Kc5 80. Rd1 Rf8+ {In this game, we tried
to explain you all the nuances, different orders and novelties of the theory
of the variation with 7...a6. In my opinion, White has many options to fight
for the advantage.} 1-0

