1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 a6 8. Be2
b5 9. Qb3 c5 10. dxc5 Bb7 {This move is less popular than 10...î Pe6 line, but
it was occaisonally tested by Peter Svidler and Giri.} 11. e5 Nfd7 12. Be3 e6 (
12... Nxe5 {This move forces a difficult endgame for Black.} 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14.
Rd1 Qc7 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 Nc6 17. Bf3 Rac8 18. Qxc6 Qxc6 19. Bxc6 Rxc6 20.
Rd2 {For sure, this is not the position that Black wants to reach while
playing Grunfeld. 1-0 (58) Meier,G (2632)-Tari,A (2412) Helsingor 2014}) (12...
Nc6) 13. O-O Qc7 (13... Nc6 {This move was not yet seen in the serious
tournament practice, however it deserves attention.} 14. a4 b4 15. Rad1 Qc7 16.
Ne4 Ncxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Nd6 Bd5 19. Rxd5 exd5 20. Qxd5) 14. Rad1 Nxc5 (
14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. f4 Bg7 17. a4 bxa4 18. Nxa4 {With a slight
advantage in the game: 1-0 (34) Tomashevsky,E (2719)-Grandelius,N (2556)
Legnica 2013}) 15. Qa3 Ne4 {A deviation from Svidler's game. I found only one
correspondence game in this position in my database.} (15... Ncd7 16. Qe7 Rc8
17. a4 $146 {A strong novelty from the Israeli grandmaster.} b4 (17... bxa4 18.
Nxa4 {With a easy play for White.  The pawn is untouchable due to:} Nxe5 19.
Qxc7 Rxc7 20. Rd8+ Bf8 21. Nxe5 {With winning a piece}) 18. Ne4 Nf8 19. Qh4 $5
(19. Nf6+ $1 {Strong and simple} Bxf6 20. Qxf6 $16 {Black's king is
irredeemably weak.}) 19... Bxe4 20. Qxe4 {White has the pair of bishops, does
not have any weaknesses and the pieces are more active. Regardless of the
inventive defense of Svidler, Gelfand won the game in a deep endgame.  1-0 (62)
Gelfand,B (2744)-Svidler,P (2734) Khanty-Mansiysk 2015}) (15... Nbd7 $2 {is a
well known mistake because of:} 16. Rc1 $16 {With a lot of threats.}) 16. Nxe4
Bxe4 17. Ng5 Bc6 (17... Bd5 $6 {Is well met by:} 18. Rxd5 $1 exd5 19. e6 {With
an initiative.}) 18. f4 Qb7 {Giri does not want to spend a tempo on h6, but
now Navara found a wonderful resource to start an attack.} (18... h6 {better
try} 19. Nf3 Rc8 20. Rc1 {White has a promising position, î ..d4 is coming
next with some threats.  1/2 (47) Holzmueller,K (2514)-Mertens,M (2429) ICCF
email 2012}) 19. Bc5 Re8 (19... Rc8 $2 {This is the best square for the rook,
but unfortunately for Black, now White starts  crushing attack.} 20. Qh3 h6 21.
Nxe6 fxe6 22. Qxe6+ $16 {With a winning position}) 20. f5 $3 {amazing resource
found by Navara.} exf5 (20... gxf5 $4 {is suicide} 21. Bh5 $18) 21. Rxf5 {The
point of White's idea.} gxf5 22. Bh5 {Even with a rook down, White has a
winning attack.} Bd5 {Only move.} (22... Rf8 23. Bxf8 Bxf8 24. Qg3 {Black is
hopeless against numerous White's threats.}) 23. Rxd5 $1 {It is a rare
occasion to see double rook sacrifice in a modern practice.} Qxd5 24. Bxf7+
Qxf7 25. Nxf7 Kxf7 26. Qb3+ {White's position is close to winning.} Kg6 27.
Qg3+ Kf7 28. Qb3+ Kg6 29. Qg3+ Kf7 30. Qf3 Nd7 31. Qd5+ Kg6 32. Qc6+ Nf6 33.
exf6 Rac8 34. Qxa6 Ra8 35. f7+ Kxf7 36. Qxb5 Rad8 37. Qb3+ Kg6 38. Qg3+ Kf7 39.
Qb3+ Kg6 40. Bd6 $2 {This mistake loses the advantage.} (40. a4 $1 {White has 
reasonable winning chances.}) 40... Bxb2 41. Qxb2 Rxd6 42. h3 Ra6 1/2-1/2

