1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Nc6 {
This move was very popular some years ago, because of a couple of opening
books which recommend it.   This is the game that changed the evaluation of
the variation and now it almost disappeared from the grandmaster practice. 
Black's idea is to provoke d5 and then to attack the centre with c6.} 8. Be2 {
We should continue developing calmly.} (8. d5 $6 {It is too early for this
move, now Black obtains very easily a very good position.} Na5 9. Qa4 c6 10.
dxc6 Nxc6 {With an excellent game for Black  0-1 (41) Abelgas,R (2319)-Gomez,J
(2526) Manila 2014}) 8... Bg4 9. d5 (9. Be3 {This normal development is well
met by:} Bxf3 10. gxf3 e5 $1 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Qb3 Nh5 $1 {Queen is coming to
h4 or f6} 13. f4 {ambitious move that leads to disaster} Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 Qxd3 15.
Rd1 Bxc3+ 16. Qxc3 Qxe4 {0-1 (16) Maurer,F (2121)-Kortschnoj,V (2600) Arvier
2006  Quick lesson by almost 80 years old legend!}) 9... Na5 10. Qb4 Bxf3 (
10... c6 $4 {This move can be seen very often in blitz games or in games of
low level.} 11. e5 Bxf3 12. exf6 $18 {It is time for Black to resign: 1-0 (22)
Farago,I (2512)-Kos,T (2310) Zadar 1999}) 11. Bxf3 c6 12. O-O {Black's main
problem is the î ..a5. If Black manages to improve the î .. position, he will
have a level game. Here, White's goal is to keep the position safe, until he
completes the development. On the other side, if White can complete the
development with î Pe3 and put his rooks in the centre, he will have a huge
advantage, because of the two bishops.} ({The greedy move} 12. dxc6 $2 {might
cause White some problems.} Nxc6 13. Qxb7 Nd4) 12... Qb6 ({A reasonable
alternative} 12... cxd5 13. exd5 {This is also possible.} (13. Nxd5 $1 {Not
the most popular, but stronger continuation.} Nxd5 (13... e6 14. Ne7+ $1 Kh8
15. Rd1 Qb6 16. Qa4 {1-0 (42) Solar,J (2208)-Jodar Arias,M (2207) ICCF email
2012}) (13... Nc6) 14. exd5 Rc8 15. Bg5 Re8 (15... f6 16. Bf4) 16. d6 {White's
two bishops have full control over the board.  1-0 (45) Johansson,L (2348)
-Thybo,J (2091) Copenhagen 2013}) 13... Rc8 14. Re1 Re8 15. Be3 Nc4 16. Bxa7 b6
17. Rac1 Bh6 18. Rc2 Nd2 19. Bxb6 (19. Bd1 $1 Nxd5 20. Qh4 Nxc3 21. Qxh6 {
White is clearly better}) 19... Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 {1/2 (26) Bareev,E (2675)
-Ivanchuk,V (2740) Elista 1998}) 13. Qa4 {The exchange of the queens is not
favourable for White, because the queen attacks the N on a5.} (13. Qxe7 $6 {
REMEMBER: We do not need a material advantage, because we already have a
strategical one.} Nc4 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Bf4 Rfe8 16. Qc7 Qxb2 {Black has at
least equal chances.  1/2 (21) Gyimesi,Z (2616)-Berkes,F (2589) Hungary 2007})
13... Nd7 14. Rd1 {This move puts pressure on Nd7 and activates the rook.} Rfd8
(14... Nc5 15. Qc2 {White Q feels very safe on a "c2" square.} Nc4 16. Rb1 Qb4
17. Bg5 Rfe8 18. Rdc1 $14 {White's pieces on the queenside are in danger.  1-0
(39) Henrichs,T (2477)-Tate,A (2321) Caleta 2014}) 15. g3 $1 {Because of this
little move, Black almost stop playing this variation. White makes a useful
waiting move, his bishop has a safe place on g2 in any case.Now is very hard
for Black to come with a constructive idea, any sensible move has a drawback. 
When the rook comes to c8 -Bg4 is a very unpleasant pin. If Nc5 then Black can
have a problem with both Black's Knights -Be3 becomes a dangerous threat.} (15.
Qc2 {This was the old main line: White protects b2-pawn and prepares the
development of the bishop on e3 or g5. The drawback of this move is that White
loses control of the important c4 square.} Rac8 16. Be3 (16. Bg5 cxd5 17. Nxd5
Rxc2 18. Nxb6 axb6 {1-0 (41) Wojtaszek,R (2705)-Nyback,T (2631) Porto Carras
2011}) 16... Qc7 17. Rac1 Nc4 18. Qe2 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 {1/2 (54) Gyimesi,Z (2646)
-Alsina Leal,D (2549) Sabadell 2011}) 15... Rac8 (15... Nc5 16. Qc2 Nc4 17. Rb1
{Good move that avoids many tricks.} Qb4 18. Kg2 Kf8 19. b3 Qxc3 20. Qxc3 Bxc3
21. bxc4 {With a clear advantage in the arising endgame.  1-0 (71)
Serradimigni,R (2561)-Janzen,N (2514) ICCF email 2012}) (15... h5 {This is
Avruch's choice, but also failed to equalize as it happened in a couple of
correspondence games.} 16. Be2 Nc5 17. Qc2 Qb4 {Posing a threat on Bc3 and Q:e4
} 18. Be3 Bxc3 19. Rac1 {Wonderful resource.} b6 (19... Qxe4 20. Qxc3 $18) (
19... Qxb2 20. Bxc5 $16) 20. Bxc5 Qxc5 21. Qxc3 Qxc3 22. Rxc3 {With small, but
long lasting advantage in the endgame.  1/2 (36) Davidov,A (2255)-Ziese,G 
(2461) ICCF email 2012}) 16. Bg4 Nc5 {Logical move, but now Black's pieces are
very bad coordinated. On the next move White will stabilize the situation and
complete development with î Pe3 which gives him a big advantage.} (16... Ra8 {
This move looks pathetic, but nothing else is left.} 17. Qc2 Ne5 18. Be2 Qc7
19. Be3 Nac4 (19... cxd5 20. Qa4 $1 {With a lot of threats.}) 20. Bd4 c5 21.
Bxe5 Nxe5 22. f4 Nd7 23. e5 {This is a dream position for White.}) 17. Qc2 e6
18. Bg5 {Wins a tempo.} Re8 19. Na4 $1 {Excellent move that highlights the
awkward position of the î ..a5.} Nxa4 20. Qxa4 cxd5 21. exd5 Nc4 22. dxe6 fxe6
23. Rac1 {So many pins.} Ne5 24. Be3 {24...Qa6 is well met by 25.Q:a6 ba 26.R:
c8 and 27.B:e6  Final accord. Excellent game by the young Dutch super GM which
now is in top 5 in the world.} 1-0

