1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qb3 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg7 6. e4 O-O 7. Be2 Nc6 8.
Nf3 e5 $1 {Instead of 8...Bg4, this pawn sacrifice became a new main line here.
} 9. d5 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 c6 {The idea is simple: Black wants to open
lines and diagonals for his pieces, even with the cost of 1 or 2 pawns. Most
often, Black's active pieces compensate the material deficit. Black has a
concrete threat now: 12...N:d5.  We have 3 main options here:} 12. Qc4 {The
main and most ambitious move.} (12. d6 {White can't keep the pawn up here and
Black obtains an easy game.} Re8 13. Qd3 b5 14. f3 Re6 15. Be3 (15. Bf4 {is
well met by:} Nh5 $11) 15... Rxd6 16. Qc2 Nh5 17. O-O Bd4 {After the exchange
of the dark-squared bishops only White can have problems.  1/2 (39) Ivanisevic,
I (2613)-Navara,D (2716) Tromso 2014}) (12. Qd1 Re8 13. dxc6 (13. O-O Nxe4 14.
Nxe4 Rxe4 15. dxc6 Rd4 16. Qb3 bxc6 {With an equal position.  1/2 (56)
Harikrishna,P (2727)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2758) Beijing 2014}) 13... Qxd1+ 14.
Nxd1 Nxe4 15. cxb7 Bxb7 16. Be3 Nd6 17. O-O Nf5 {Black has at least enough
compensation for the pawn  : 1/2 (68) Kozul,Z (2630)-Sadzikowski,D (2492)
Jerusalem 2015}) 12... b5 $1 {The main and most ambitious move, Black
sacrifices another pawn in order to develop quickly all his forces.} 13. Qb3 (
13. Qxc6 {Principal decision which was tested in some very high rated games
recently. Unfortunately for us, for now Black equalized with some very sharp
and forced lines.} Bd7 14. Qd6 Re8 {This is first critical position in this
line:} 15. f3 {First choice of the engines, we will see in a following game
how deep is the preparation of the young Chinese super star Wei Yi.} (15. Bg5
$1 {This was another line that I want to reccomend you.} b4 {Again this pawn
sacrifice destroys the coordination between White's pieces.} 16. Qxb4 Nxd5 17.
Nxd5 Qxg5 18. O-O Rab8 19. Qd6 Bh3 20. Nf4 Bg4 21. Bxg4 Be5 22. Qd7 Qxf4 23. g3
Qf6 {White has 2 pawns up, but opposite coloured bishops and weaknesses on b2
and f2 are very vulnerable. Giri very convincingly hold this position. I will
recommend you this line for White, because it is quite safe for White and not
everybody enjoys playing such positions with Black.  1/2 (48) Aronian,L (2797)
-Giri,A (2784) Wijk aan Zee 2015}) 15... Nh5 16. Be3 f5 17. Qa3 {It seems that
White holds everything under control and then suddenly Black sacrifices the
third pawn!!!} b4 $1 {Brilliant. Black activates his rook and puts more
pressure on h8-a1 diagonal.} (17... fxe4 {is well met by} 18. Nxe4 $16) 18.
Qxb4 Rb8 19. Qa3 fxe4 20. f4 Qh4+ 21. g3 Nxg3 22. Bf2 Qh3 23. Bxg3 Rec8 $3 {
Amazing position White is piece and a pawn up but they do not have nothing
better than to repeat the moves.} 24. Bf1 Qg4 25. Be2 Qh3 26. Bf1 Qg4 27. Be2 {
1/2 (27) Ding,L (2766)-Wei,Y (2706) Wijk aan Zee 2016}) 13... cxd5 (13... Re8 {
This typical move can be met with:} 14. O-O Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Rxe4 16. Bf3 Qxd5 {
Otherwise Black will be just with a pawn down without any compensation.} 17.
Qxd5 cxd5 18. Bxe4 dxe4 {Black definitely has some compensation for the
exchange, but he still has to prove that it is enough.}) (13... a5 14. dxc6 b4
15. Na4 Qc7 16. Be3 Be6 17. Qc2 {White was just two pawns up in a recent game:
1-0 (59) Talla,V (2447)-Kriebel,T (2465) Czech Republic 2015}) 14. exd5 Re8 (
14... b4 15. Qxb4 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 17. O-O Qe5 18. Bf3 Rb8 19. Qa4 Qd4 20.
Qxd4 Bxd4 21. Rd1 Bg7 22. Be3 {White has good chances to convert his advantage.
1/2 (35) Riemersma,L (2426)-Swinkels,R (2522) Amsterdam 2013}) 15. O-O b4 {
Again this sacrifice is Black's chance to fight for the initiative.} 16. Qxb4
Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Rxe2 18. Qc4 (18. Rd1 $1 $146 {This move is the improvement in
this line! White poses a threat of Ne7 check.} {The main line goes:} a5 19.
Ne7+ Qxe7 20. Qxe7 Rxe7 21. Rd8+ Bf8 22. Bh6 Bb7 23. Bxf8 Rxd8 24. Bxe7 Rd2 25.
Bf6 {White definitely has winning chances, because of the pawn up and the
weakness of Black's king}) 18... Re5 19. Nc7 Be6 20. Nxe6 Rxe6 21. Be3 Bxb2 22.
Rab1 Bf6 {White has a tiny edge here.} 23. Rfd1 Rd6 24. Rxd6 Qxd6 25. g3 Rb8
26. Rxb8+ Qxb8 27. Qc6 Kg7 28. Kg2 Qb2 29. Qd5 a6 30. a4 Qe5 31. Qb7 Qd6 32. h4
h5 33. Bb6 Qd3 34. Qc6 Qe2 35. Bc5 Qe6 36. Qxe6 fxe6 37. Kf3 Kf7 38. Ke4 Bc3
39. Kd3 Be1 40. Kc4 Ke8 41. Be3 Kd7 42. Kd4 Kd6 43. Bf4+ Kd7 44. Be3 Kd6 45.
Bf4+ Kd7 46. Be3 1/2-1/2

