1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Na6 8.
Be2 c5 9. d5 e6 10. O-O exd5 11. exd5 Bf5 {The most popular move in this
position.} 12. Bg5 $1 {In the spirit of this database, I  did not offer  the
main line, but rather something fresh and unexpired. A recent Ding Lieren's
game in Tata Steel 2016 grabbed my attention. Despite the fact that the things
quickly go wrong for White there, I believe that I found the idea and the
preparation of the Chinese grandmaster. See comments on move 12} Qb6 (12... Re8
{This move can transpose to a previous game.} 13. Rad1 h6 14. Be3) (12... h6
13. Be3 Qb6 (13... Re8 {transpose to Anand-Carlsen}) 14. b3 $6 (14. Nd2 $1 $146
{I believe that this is Ding Lieren's analysis and he just forgot in which
moment exactly Nd2 is very strong.   The N is going to even c4 or b3.} Qxb2 $5
{is perfectly met by} 15. Rab1 Bxb1 16. Rxb1 Qa3 $2 (16... b5 17. Nxb5 Qe5 18.
Bf3 {With an excellent compensation for the exchange.}) 17. Rxb7 {And White
wins material.}) 14... Rfe8 15. Nd2 $2 Nd7 {White was in trouble in a recent
game.  1/2 (64) Ding,L (2766)-Van Wely,L (2640) Wijk aan Zee 2016}) 13. Qh4 {
A nice maneuvre and one of the reasons which I like 12.Bg5} Rfe8 (13... Ng4 14.
Rae1 $3 {Wonderful prophylactic move with a deep idea.  White protects the Be2
and is ready to meet Q:b2 with Nd1-e3} Qxb2 (14... h6 15. Be7 Rfe8 16. d6 $16 {
You can see how strong is the d-pawn now.}) 15. Nd1 Qb6 16. h3 Nf6 17. Ne3 {
White's initiative is more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 14. Bb5 Re4
{Maybe this is not the best move according to the engines, but this is the
best practical chance for Black to achieve some active play.} (14... Red8 15.
Rad1 $16 {This is not the position that Black wants to achieve in this line.})
(14... Bd7 15. Bc4 $16 {Leaves Black without counterplay.}) (14... Nd7 15. d6
$1 $14) 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxa6 Nxg5 {Strange mistake. Now, White has material
advantage and winning attack.} (16... Qxa6 $1 17. Be7 Bxb2 18. Rae1 Bf6 19.
Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Re7 $1 {White will have some technical difficulties, but his
position is winning.} Nxd5 $6 21. Ng5 $16) 17. Nxg5 Qxa6 18. Qxh7+ {The rest
of the game I leave without comments. White is simply winning.} Kf8 19. b3 Rd8
20. Rad1 Qd6 21. Qh4 f6 22. Ne4 Qe5 23. Nxc5 Rxd5 24. Rxd5 Qxd5 25. Qb4 Kg8 26.
Qc4 Qxc4 27. bxc4 b6 28. Nb3 Bf8 29. c5 bxc5 30. Rc1 Be6 31. Nxc5 Bxa2 32. Nd7
Be7 33. Ra1 Bd5 34. Rxa7 Be4 35. Rc7 Kf7 36. Nc5 Bd5 37. Nd3 Be4 38. Nf4 1-0

