1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Na6 {
This is so-called Prins variation that was the favourite reply of Gary
Kasparov when he faced Russian System against the Grunfeld. The idea is to
support c5 which will be Black's next move.} 8. Be2 c5 9. d5 ({The naive} 9.
dxc5 $2 Be6 10. Qb5 Rc8 {is Black's dream in Grunfeld.}) 9... e6 10. O-O exd5
11. exd5 {Almost forced, we reach this position.  How can we evaluate it: It
is obvious that this is strategically risky for Black, because of the White's
d-pawn. On the other side, Black has a lot of pieces to block the pawn and his
pieces have a lot of freedom.  Black has several active plans here. One is to
take control over the e4 square and trying to exchange Nf6 to the Nc3, then
Black's dark-squared bishop will put pressure over the b2-pawn and d5-pawn
that might become weak. Another idea is to play b6-Nb4 and Bb7 or Ba6.  What
White should do!? White should try to support d-pawn and very often can push
it to d6, while Black should always be worried about it. Also White should try
to keep Na6 passive. Sometimes, White has an idea to start an attack with Qh4
in the moment when Black is busy handling the d-pawn.} Re8 {If World Champion
plays this move, I believe that we should call this a main line nowadays.} 12.
Bg5 $5 {Not the most popular, but very tricky move.} (12. Rd1) (12. Be3 {are
more common alternatives.}) 12... h6 {The pin is annoying, so this move is
necessary to be played.} (12... Bf5 13. Rad1 h6 14. Be3) 13. Be3 {It looks
that White just lost a tempo, but we will see an idea to provoke h6 later in
the game.} Bf5 {The most active square for the bishop.} {The question is:
which rook ?} 14. Rad1 {The small nuance is that when we play with the a-rook
on d1, in some variations, we can leave b2 pawn without protection, because B:
b2 will not be with tempo.} Ne4 {Black plays the most natural move, but this
leads by force to a very unpleasant position.} (14... Qb6 $5 15. b3 $6 {this
is waste of tempo.} (15. Rd2 $1 $146 {With the idea to double the rooks looks
better for White.}) 15... Rad8 16. Rd2 Ng4 {Black has a reasonable counter
play. 0-1 (67) Wojtaszek,R (2713)-Ponomariov,R (2729) Poikovsky 2012}) 15. Nxe4
Bxe4 16. Qc1 $14 {The point of White's idea. White wins a tempo by attacking
the h6 pawn.} Qf6 (16... Nb4 $146 {is the first line on my engine.} 17. Qxc5
Nc2 18. d6 {And it is obvious that something is wrong with Black's position.})
17. Bxh6 Qxb2 18. Qxb2 Bxb2 19. Ng5 Bd4 20. Nxe4 Rxe4 21. Bf3 Re7 {With 2
bishops and passed d-pawn, White has a very pleasant advantage.} 22. d6 Rd7 23.
Bf4 Nb4 24. Rd2 Re8 25. Rc1 Re6 26. h4 Be5 27. Bxe5 Rxe5 28. Bxb7 {Anand
decided to force a draw.} ({after} 28. g3 Kg7 {White still has decent chances
to torture his opponent}) 28... Rxb7 29. d7 Nc6 30. d8=Q+ Nxd8 31. Rxd8+ Kg7
32. Rd2 1/2-1/2

