1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Bg4 {
Long time ago, this system was the main weapon against Smyslov Variation.
Black tries to eliminate the knight on f3 and then to put pressure over
d4-pawn with the maneuvre Nfd7-b6 and Nc6. When the pawn moves forward "d4-d5",
then Black can attack the centre by c6 or e6.} 8. Be3 Nfd7 9. Nd2 {I recommend
you this very rare move. In 2015, this move was tried twice in very high rated
games and Black could not equalize both times. But this move was tried first
long time ago, by the 5th World Champion-Mihail Botvinik. When such an expert
in Grunfeld, like Svidler struggles in this position, this definitely has a
future. The idea is simple: White just avoids doubling pawns on f-line. Then
with h3 or f3 attacks the bishop, later the î .. from d2 can be useful at c4
or b3.} Nb6 (9... Na6 $5 10. h3 Nb6 11. Qb3 Be6 12. d5 Bd7 13. Bxa6 $1 {This
move ruined Black's pawn structure.} (13. a4 c6 14. a5 cxd5 15. exd5 Nc8 16.
Be2 Nd6 {Black is solid}) 13... bxa6 14. O-O c6 15. dxc6 Bxc6 16. Rfd1 Qc7 17.
Rac1 Qb7 18. Qb4 {With an obvious advantage. White's plan is simple, î .. from
d2 will go to b3 with a lot of threats.  1/2 (42) Wojtaszek,R (2733)-Navara,D 
(2724) Biel 2015}) 10. Qc5 {A modern approach in this type of positions. The
queen stops c5 and can be transferred to g5 or go to an ideal square in this
structure-a3.} (10. Qd3 {This is Botvinik's choice for this position.} c6 11.
f3 Be6 12. Rd1 Na6 13. a3 Qd7 14. Qc2 Nc7 15. Nb3 Bc4 16. Be2 Bxe2 17. Qxe2
Rad8 18. O-O {White's position seems promising. 1/2 (79) Botvinnik,M-Smyslov,V
The Hague/Moscow 1948}) 10... c6 (10... e5 {This novelty looks logical but
failed to equalize.} 11. d5 c6 12. f3 Bd7 (12... Bc8 13. Rd1 cxd5 14. exd5 N8d7
15. Qa3 $14 {The position is similar to Prince Variation. White's d-pawn and
more active pieces gives him advantage.}) 13. Rd1 cxd5 14. exd5 Na6 15. Bxa6
bxa6 16. O-O {White has a dangerous d-passed pawn and a better pawn structure,
on the other side Black has two bishops. I prefer to play with white pieces in
this position, because he has no weaknesses and a easier game.}) 11. f3 (11. h3
{This is less ambitious but safer option, which is also quite playable.} Be6
12. Be2 a5 13. Rd1 Nc8 14. d5 cxd5 15. exd5 Bf5 16. O-O {White's pieces are
better developed.  1-0 (37) Jarabinsky,M (2164)-Rovchakov,V (2020) LSS email
2012}) 11... Be6 12. O-O-O {Very interesting setup} f5 {Interesting decision,
Black fights for the control of the important d5-square.} 13. e5 {White leaves
the d5-square, but gains space on the king side and isolates Black's
dark-squared bishop.} N8d7 14. Qa3 {Remember this!!! White's î B feels very
comfortable at a3: controls c5 and attacks on e7.} Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. h4 $1
{White's attack is starting. He has an easy plan - to open "h" and "g" files.}
h6 17. Nb1 $5 {White decides to improve N position.} (17. Kb1 {With the idea
g4 that deserves attention.}) 17... Nb6 18. Nc3 $14 {We can evaluate the
position as slightly better for White. I will leave next moves without
comments, because they are not relevant for the topic, after a lot of
adventures this game ended in a draw.} Be6 19. Kb1 Qd7 20. Bd3 Nd5 21. Nxd5
Bxd5 22. Ka1 e6 23. Qc5 Rf7 24. Qc1 Kh7 25. Rh3 c5 26. dxc5 Qa4 27. Bb1 Bxe5
28. Bxh6 Rc8 29. Be3 Rc6 30. h5 g5 31. Rhh1 Bb3 32. Bxg5 Ra6 33. Rh4 Qa5 34.
Bd2 Qd8 35. Re1 Rd7 36. Rb4 Bxa2 37. Bxa2 Qa5 38. Qc4 Rxd2 39. Rxb7+ Kh8 40.
Rb5 Qa3 41. Rb8+ Kh7 42. Rb7+ Kh6 43. Qf4+ Bxf4 44. bxa3 Rxa3 45. Rb2 Kxh5 46.
Rxd2 Bxd2 47. Rxe6 Be3 48. c6 Bd4+ 49. Kb1 Rc3 50. Bd5 Rc5 51. Bb3 Kg5 52. Bd1
Kf4 53. g4 Be5 54. gxf5 Kxf5 55. Rh6 Kg5 56. Re6 Kf5 57. Rh6 1/2-1/2

