1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Nfd7 {
This system is a rare guest in the tournament practice.  White starts a
so-called Smyslov maneuvre immediately, without î Pg4. This does not pose
immediate threats to White's center and with an energetic play White gains an
advantage.  I am offering you a plan with 0-0-0 and later to start a king side
attack by h2-h4.} 8. Be3 Nb6 (8... Nc6 9. O-O-O Nb6 10. Qb3 a5 11. a3 Bg4 12.
d5 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Ne5 14. Be2 {Similar to a main game, White has two bishops
and chances for the attack on  king side.  1-0 (33) Bajarani,U (2436)
-Shtyrenkov,V (2341) Alushta 2013}) (8... a6 {Black prepares b5, so now is a
good idea to choose a plan with short castle.} 9. Be2 b5 10. Qb3 Nc6 11. O-O
Nb6 12. Rad1 Qd6 13. h3 Bb7 14. Qc2 Rac8 15. Rfe1 {White has full control over
the centre and an easy game 1-0 (45) Rusev,K (2537)-Gheng,J (2338) Boeblingen
2009}) 9. Qc5 {The best square for the queen. From here the queen can go to
"g5" or "a3"} Bg4 10. O-O-O N8d7 11. Qg5 $1 {There is no need to move the
queen on the "a3" square far from the action.} Bxf3 12. gxf3 {Doubling the
pawns is not enough compensation for the two bishops.} e6 13. h4 h5 (13... Qxg5
14. hxg5 {With a hopeless endgame for Black.}) 14. f4 Nf6 15. Be2 Qd7 16. Rhg1
Kh8 17. d5 $1 {Freeing the d4-square for the bishop  White's attack is
unstoppable.} exd5 18. Bd4 Nh7 19. Bxg7+ Kxg7 20. Qxh5 Nf6 21. Qg5 Qc6 22. exd5
{White has a mating attack and a material advantage.} Qc5 23. h5 Na4 $4 {Last
mistake in an already lost position} (23... Rh8) 24. h6+ {With mate in a
couple of moves.  Perfect game by the current Russian champion.} 1-0

