1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 c6 {This
move is not so ambitious, because it does not place pressure on the center
immediately. The idea is to play quickly b7-b5 and to win some space on the
queenside.} 8. Be2 {White simply finishes the development.} Be6 {With this
move Black wins a tempo. However, White has a slight advantage due to the
strong centre and more naturally developed pieces.} (8... b5 {White has 2
options here:} 9. Qb3 Qa5 10. e5 Be6 11. Qc2 Bf5 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nd5 14.
O-O Qd8 15. Ne4 {White has a clear advantage.  1-0 (35) Jakovenko,D (2737)
-Borisek,J (2548) Dresden 2008}) 9. Qd3 Na6 10. O-O Qb6 11. h3 {Since Black
still has no direct threats, White has time for this useful move. Now the
bishop on e3 will be secure.} Rad8 12. a3 Bc8 13. Be3 Qc7 14. b4 {Prophylactic
move against Nc5} Nb8 {It is hard to find something better for Black.} 15. Qc2
{White's plan is easy. First, to put the rooks on d1 and c1 and then to try a
breakthrough on the queen side or in the centre.} Rfe8 16. Rfd1 a6 17. Rac1 e6
18. Bg5 h6 19. Bh4 Nbd7 20. e5 Nh5 21. Bxd8 Qxd8 22. Qd2 {White's position is
completely winning, but MVL continues the fight only because this was a blitz
game.} Bf8 23. Ne4 Kh7 24. Bf1 Ng7 25. a4 Be7 26. b5 axb5 27. axb5 Nb6 28. bxc6
bxc6 29. Qa5 Bd7 30. Nc5 Nd5 31. Qxd8 Rxd8 32. Nxd7 Rxd7 33. Rxc6 Nf5 34. g3
Kg7 35. h4 Bb4 36. Rc4 Ba5 37. Bh3 Nfe7 38. Bf1 Nf5 39. Ra1 Bb6 40. Rb1 Ba5 41.
Rb5 Bd8 42. Rb8 Bc7 43. Rb7 Re7 44. Rc1 Bb6 45. Rxe7 Ndxe7 46. Rc4 Nd5 47. Bd3
Nfe7 48. Be4 Nc7 49. Kg2 Kf8 50. Rb4 Ba5 51. Ra4 Bb6 52. Nd2 Kg7 53. Nb3 f5 54.
exf6+ Kxf6 55. Nc5 Bxc5 56. dxc5 Ke5 57. f4+ Kf6 {The idea of 7...c6 followed
by b5 or Be6 does not place any immediate threats and White obtains a better
